{
  "doc_id": "32694",
  "text": "In recent years, Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) have become the dominant paradigm in generic object detection [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . The same trend is also true for the pedestrian detection [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . Some of the pioneer works for CNN based pedestrian detection [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] used R-CNN framework [CITATION_10] , which is still the most popular framework. RPN+BF [CITATION_11] was the first work to use Region Proposal Network (RPN); it used boosted forest for improving pedestrian detection performance. This work also pointed out some problems in the underlying classification branch of Faster RCNN [CITATION_12] , namely that the resolution of the feature maps and class-imbalance. However, RPN+BF despite achieving good performances had a shortcoming of not being optimized in a closed form. After the initial works, Faster RCNN [CITATION_13] became most popular framework with wide range of literature deploying it for pedestrian detection [CITATION_14] [CITATION_15] [CITATION_16] [CITATION_17] [CITATION_18] .",
